Kenyans have up to the end of today to submit proposals for consideration in the 2017-18 financial year budgetary allocation.The National Treasury, which unveiled the draft budget policy statement for public scrutiny in November, had given institutions, the private sector, NGOs and individuals until December 30 to give their inputs before it is tabled before the Cabinet for approval.The 2017-18 budget has given priority to agriculture, energy, infrastructure, ICT, health and education, among other sectors.Cabinet Secretary Henry Rotich plans to spend Sh2.275 trillion ( 27.5 per cent of gross domestic product) in 2017-18 financial year starting July 1.This is 11.1 per cent more than current financial year&rsquo;s Sh2.048 trillion that ends on June 30 next year.&ldquo;The proposal should take into account measures that will spur and, or, sustain economic growth, strengthen devolution, create wealth and employment opportunities, and reduce poverty in line with Vision 2030,&rdquo; Treasury Principal Secretary Kamau Thugge said in a public notice on November 28. He said the proposals should outline ways to create a conducive business environment, how to attract investments in agriculture, modernise seaports, airports, rail, road and oil sectors.The proposals should also provide guidelines to &ldquo;reform tax systems and streamline revenue administration&rdquo;.In the draft budget, the National Treasury has allocated agriculture rural and urban development Sh46.6 billion, a slight increase from the current Sh46.5 billion.Energy, infrastructure and ICT budget has been cut to Sh509.4 billion from Sh529.2 billion.Education will receive Sh371.8 billion up from Sh339.9 billion.